DP William Ruto’s allies in the Rift Valley are split over the emergence of a “rebel group” of MPs who might pose a threat to his 2022 presidential ambition. Uasin Gishu Governor Jackson Mandago and Kesses MP Swarrup Mishra have warned the “rebel MPs”, led by Nandi Hills Alfred Keter, that would be not be entertained. They will threaten the interests of the Kalenjin community, he said. Read : Prepare for a knockout in 2022, Ruto tells rivals The arrest of Keter last week in a Treasury Bills controversy has sparked heated debate in the region. “We want to tell Keter and his friends they will not be allowed to put roadblocks on the DP’s route to State House,” Mandago said in Turbo during prayers attended by the DP on Sunday. Others being viewed as “rebels” include Cherangany MP Joshua Kuttuny, Sila Tiren of Moiben and Kangogo Bowen of Marakwet East, who have defended Keter, claiming that he was being targeted politically by the government. Click here for the latest political news